<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
Female unknown. The original description states that one male and one female were available, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, JFG" journalOrPublisher="Dissertation, The Ohio State University" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42780382" refId="B8" refString="Clarke, JFG, 1965. Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick, Volume V: 1-581. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London. https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42780382" title="Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick, Volume V: 1 - 581. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42780382" year="1965">Clarke (1965)</bibRefCitation>
reported that both are males. The asymmetry in the male valvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 35–36" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 35 - 36. Male genitalia of Rhamphura 35 R. depressa (Meyrick, 1931), holotype, slide JFGC No. 8061 36 R. dimota (Meyrick, 1931), lectotype, slide JFGC No. 8062." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1087.64382.figures35-36" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/649321" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">36</figureCitation>
) is an artefact of preparation due to a partly folded left valva on the slide mount. 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="R." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="R. dimota" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dimota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">R. dimota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="R." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="R. depressa" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="depressa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">R. depressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly the bronzy-fuscous wings, long and narrow valvae and free apodemes on sternum VIII. For these reasons, we reclassify 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nupponen 1 &amp; Sihvonen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Nupponen 1 &amp; Sihvonen" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Scythrididae" genus="Scythris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scythris dimota" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Scythris dimota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Meyrick, 1931 as 
<taxonomicName authority="Landry, 1991" authorityName="Nupponen 1 &amp; Sihvonen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Scythrididae" genus="Rhamphura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhamphura dimota" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dimota">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Rhamphura dimota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Meyrick, 1931) new combination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
